    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nI was rather suprised to discover that using a multi-component extension, like say \"service.erb\" or \"scala.html\" doesn't work in the extension table passed to vim.filetype.add. \n\nI can see why this might be the case, but it isn't entirely clear from the documentation for vim.filetype.add. I eventually ended up reading the source code in filetype.lua to confirm how it worked. \n\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nRead [documentation for vim.filetype.add](https://neovim.io/doc/user/lua/#vim.filetype.add())\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nDocumentation should say something to the effect of \"the extension is everything after the *last* \".\" in the filename, if any\".\n\nAlternatively, support multi-component extensions, although that may not be feasible for performance reasons., and would be more of a feature request than a bug fix.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nn/a\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nn/a\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nn/a\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nn/a\n\n### Installation\n\ntarball from release page",
